\begin_layout Section
Proposed ISSRR Model for Contentious Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the proposed ISCR model describes two primary groups in which opposing class members seek to turn the other to their side of belief of contentious information, it does not describe a situation in which there are multiple final recovered states of contentious information belief. A new model must be proposed to handle this type of social network contentious information spread.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a basic ISR modeling of a polarized social network group that is presented with contentious information, leading to two final recovered beliefs, representing individuals who eventually make up their mind concerning the information and have lost interest in it, pending any relevant new information. As the new information is discovered by the network population, individuals form an initial opinion and many will choose to begin to spread the information opinion stance they have decided to follow among their friends and fellow social network members. At this point, two such spreader groups will arise, each pushing people via online social media tweets and posts to come to their 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

side" of the contentious information in the hopes of gaining additional spreaders who, hopefully, finally settle on their preferred of the two recovered states. We shall call this the Ignorant-Spreader-Spreader-Recovered-Recovered (ISSRR) model, which is visually depicted in Figure 
